sec.p:
The experimented results of conductivity for PCBs revel a nonlinear variation with CB concentration39–42. In fact, the relationship between PCB conductivity and CB amount is nonlinear. Also, only the networked nanoparticles produce and control the conductivity of samples43,44. Accordingly, it is believed that the PCB conductivity links to the network volume fraction (ϕN) by a simple equation with ϕN power of 2 as:1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\:\sigma\:=A{{\varphi\:}_{N}}^{2}+B{\varphi\:}_{N}$$\end{document}

The polymer – filler interfacial tension (γpf) directly manipulates the nanocomposite conductivity, since the higher interfacial tension provides more contacts among nanoparticles facilitating the charge transferring28. In addition, less polymer surface tension (γp) is desirable to enhance the interfacial tension, due to their high difference with filler surface energy (γf). Furthermore, the interphase conductivity (σi) has a straight role in the conductivity, as the network includes both filler and interphase12. Therefore, A can be connected to these parameters as:2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\:A=\frac{{\gamma\:}_{pf}}{{\gamma\:}_{p}}{\sigma\:}_{i}$$\end{document}

γ
pf can be estimated by the following equation28:3\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\:{\gamma\:}_{pf}={{\gamma\:}_{f}+{\gamma\:}_{p}-2\left({\gamma\:}_{f}{\gamma\:}_{p}\right)}^{\frac{1}{2}}$$\end{document}

which develops A in Eq. to this form:4\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\:A={\sigma\:}_{i}\frac{{{\gamma\:}_{f}+{\gamma\:}_{p}-2\left({\gamma\:}_{f}{\gamma\:}_{p}\right)}^{\frac{1}{2}}}{{\gamma\:}_{p}}$$\end{document}

Additionally, B term in Eq. 1 can be linked to the tunneling features like tunnelling distance (λ), contact diameter (d) and polymer tunnel resistivity (p). The contact diameter is the diameter of CBs in the tunneling region. Actually, the tunneling distance is the distance among the neighboring CBs, but the contact diameter is the width of adjacent CBs in the tunneling region. Narrower tunnels with higher contact diameter produce the poorer tunnelling resistance increasing the conductivity of samples. Thus, the tunnelling distance and contact diameter directly and inversely manage the conductivity, respectively. Furthermore, p directly manages the tunnelling resistance, as a higher p prevents the electron transfer through tunnels. So, p conversely handles the electron transferring in the composites. According to this description, B is expressed by:5\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\:B=\frac{({\frac{d}{\lambda\:})}^{2}}{p}$$\end{document}

Now, Eq. 1 can be advanced by Eqs. 4 and 5 as:6\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\:\sigma\:={\sigma\:}_{i}\frac{{{\gamma\:}_{f}+{\gamma\:}_{p}-2\left({\gamma\:}_{f}{\gamma\:}_{p}\right)}^{\frac{1}{2}}}{{\gamma\:}_{p}}{{\varphi\:}_{N}}^{2}+\frac{({\frac{d}{\lambda\:})}^{2}}{p}{\varphi\:}_{N}$$\end{document}

ϕN is expressed by:7\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\phi_N = f\phi_{eff}$$\end{document}

f is formulated in the PCBs by the percolation onset (ϕp) and ϕeff28 as:8\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$f = \frac{\phi_{eff}^{1/3} - \phi_{p}^{1/3} }{1-\phi_{p}^{1/3}}$$\end{document}

In the PCBs, the effective volume proportion of filler (CBs and interphase) is formulated as:9\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\phi_{eff} = \phi_f(1+\frac{t}{R})^3$$\end{document}

Additionally, ϕp is controlled by some factors, including CB size, γp, γpf, and t, because all these parameters dictate the network creation in the nanocomposites47,48. Bigger CB nanoparticles and thinner interphase raise the ϕp. Also, higher γp reduces the interfacial tension (Eq. 3), raising the ϕp, as low interfacial tension eases the wettability and disperses the nanoparticles more effectively within the system49. So, both t and γpf conversely handle the percolation threshold, while CB radius and γp have direct roles. Based on these observations, ϕp was formulated for PCBs28 as:10\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\phi_p = \frac{R \gamma_p}{1000t \gamma_{pf}}$$\end{document}

When f from Eq. 8 is substituted into Eq. 7, ϕN can be given by:11\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\phi_N = (\frac{\phi_{eff}^{1/3} - \phi_{p}^{1/3}}{1-\phi_{p}^{1/3}}) \phi_{eff}$$\end{document}
